<subSubSection pageId="198" pageNumber="802" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="198.[2057,2665,1442,1866]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eisentraut" authorityYear="1969" box="[2058,2315,1557,1591]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Hylomyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="198" pageNumber="802" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">Hylomyscus grandis</taxonomicName>
was previously subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[2161,2249,1596,1630]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Hylomyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="198" pageNumber="802" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aeta">H. aeta</taxonomicName>
but elevated to a full species based on its larger size. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="198" pageNumber="802" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="802" startId="198.[2057,2229,1675,1709]" targetBox="[1442,2033,1448,1861]" targetPageId="198">
<paragraph blockId="198.[2057,2665,1442,1866]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2057,2233,1675,1709]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from four specimens collected from upper slopes of Mt Oku, W Cameroon.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="198" pageNumber="802" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="198.[2057,2665,1442,1866]" lastBlockId="198.[1442,2648,1872,2378]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2057,2300,1793,1827]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 89-110 mm, tail 130-150 mm, ear 15-20, hindfoot 18 22 mm; weight 25-41 g. Fur of the Mount Oku Wood Mouse is fine and soft, grayish brown to bright cinnamon-brown on dorsum and flanks and whitish gray on venter, nose, upper lips, chin, and lower cheeks. Dorsal and ventral colors are sharply delineated. Tail is very long (c.145% of head-body length) and appears naked exceptfor tuft of hair at tip. Fifth digit on hindfoot is opposable and almost as long as second to fourth digits. Females have two pairs of nipples.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1444,2111,2107,2141]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="198.[1442,2648,1872,2378]" box="[1444,2111,2107,2141]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1444,1554,2107,2141]" pageId="198" pageNumber="802">Habitat.</emphasis>
Montane forest at ¢.2100 m ofaltitude.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
